/F2 15 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 732.0 Tm (Voicing the Past: Acoustic Trade-offs in the Restoration of Eighteenth-Century Pipe Organs) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 718.0 Tm () Tj
/F1 9 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 704.0 Tm (Cornelis Reinhart and Beatrix Vogel) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (Journal of Historical Acoustics, Vol. 19, No. 1 \(1999\) - JID-010) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Restoring a historic pipe organ forces a choice between two incompatible fidelities: to the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (instrument as it was originally voiced and to the instrument as later generations altered) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (and loved it. Through three case restorations we examine the acoustic consequences of each) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (choice, focusing on wind pressure, pipe voicing, and the temperament to which the instrument) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (is tuned. We argue that no restoration is acoustically neutral and that every decision) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (silently privileges one historical moment over others.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (A pipe organ is rarely the instrument its builder finished. Over centuries it accumulates) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (repairs, enlargements, retunings, and changes of taste, each leaving an acoustic mark. When) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (a restorer is engaged, the first and least technical question is the hardest: to which) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (version of the instrument should it be restored?) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (This paper approaches that question through its acoustic consequences. Drawing on three) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (restorations of eighteenth-century instruments, we show that the choice of target era is not) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (a matter of authenticity in the abstract but a concrete decision about how the organ will) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (sound.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Wind Pressure and Attack) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (The pressure of the wind supplied to the pipes governs the loudness, the speech, and above) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (all the attack of each note. Original eighteenth-century instruments ran at modest pressures) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (that gave a gentle, slightly hesitant speech prized by their builders. Nineteenth-century) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (renovators frequently raised the pressure for a bolder, more immediate sound suited to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (larger congregations.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (Restoring the original pressure recovers the historic attack but can leave the instrument) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (sounding underpowered in a space later enlarged to seat more listeners. The restorer must) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (decide whether to honour the pipes' designed speech or the room's present demands, and these) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm (often conflict.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 230.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (Voicing the Pipes) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (Voicing, the fine adjustment of each pipe's mouth and windway, determines its tone colour.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (It is also the most easily lost layer of an organ's history, because later voicers routinely) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (overwrote earlier work without record. Recovering original voicing therefore often means) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (reconstructing it from indirect evidence rather than restoring something still present.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (Where original voicing survives on even a few pipes, it becomes a reference for the rest,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (but matching new work to it is an interpretive act. Two skilled restorers given the same) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (surviving pipes will produce subtly different ensembles, and neither can claim to have) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 86.0 Tm (simply uncovered the truth.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 72.0 Tm () Tj
