/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 732.0 Tm (Temperament and the Audible Compromise) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 718.0 Tm (The temperament to which an organ is tuned, the precise way the octave is divided, is) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 704.0 Tm (perhaps the most audible of all restoration choices. Eighteenth-century instruments were) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (often tuned in unequal temperaments that make some keys sweet and others harsh, a quality) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm (central to the music written for them.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 662.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 648.0 Tm (Restoring such a temperament brings the original repertoire to life but can render later) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 634.0 Tm (music, composed for equal temperament, unplayable in certain keys. Here the conflict between) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 620.0 Tm (historical moments becomes unavoidable and public: the organ literally cannot serve both) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 606.0 Tm (eras at once, and the restorer must choose which centuries of music the instrument will be) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 592.0 Tm (able to speak.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 578.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm (Conclusion) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 546.0 Tm (Organ restoration is a sequence of acoustic commitments, each favouring one stratum of the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 532.0 Tm (instrument's history. Wind pressure, voicing, and temperament cannot all be returned to a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 518.0 Tm (single moment without loss elsewhere. We conclude that honesty about these trade-offs,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 504.0 Tm (rather than an unattainable neutrality, should guide restoration practice.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 490.0 Tm () Tj
